solution.p:
The definition of the derivative is
f'(x)= \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}
This problem gives us the numerator, f(x+h)-f(x).  So,

\frac{3+6\sqrt{x+h}-(3+6\sqrt{x})}{h} = \frac{6\sqrt{x+h}-6\sqrt{x}}{h} =\frac{(6\sqrt{x+h}-6\sqrt{x})(6\sqrt{x+h}+6\sqrt{x})}{h(6\sqrt{x+h}+6\sqrt{x})} 
= \frac{36\mathopen{}\left(x+h\right)-36x}{h(6\sqrt{x+h}+6\sqrt{x})} = \frac{36h}{h(6\sqrt{x+h}+6\sqrt{x})} = \frac{36h}{6 h(\sqrt{x+h}+\sqrt{x})} 
Finally, we can divide to get
=\frac{6}{\sqrt{x+h}+\sqrt{x}}
That means A=6, while B=C=1.

