solution.p:
The function \displaystyle y=\frac{2x}{4x+7} is a quotient of two functions, say f(x)= 2x and g(x)=4x+7.  Then taking the derivatives we get f'(x)=2 and g'(x)=4.  Finally, the quotient rule says that 
\left[\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right]'=\frac{g(x)f'(x)-f(x)g'(x)}{\left[g(x)\right]^2}
so y'= \frac{(4x+7) \cdot (2)  - (2x)\cdot (4)}{(4x+7)^2}= \frac{14}{(4 x + 7)^2}.

The function \displaystyle y=\frac{x^{3}}{\sqrt{x}+10x^{9}} is a quotient of two functions, say f(x)= x^{3} and g(x)=\sqrt{x}+10x^{9}.  Then taking the derivatives we get f'(x)=3x^{2} and g'(x)=\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}+10\cdot 9x^{8}.  Finally, the quotient rule says that 
\left[\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right]'=\frac{g(x)f'(x)-f(x)g'(x)}{\left[g(x)\right]^2}
so y'= \frac{(\sqrt{x}+10x^{9}) \cdot (3x^{2})  - (x^{3})\cdot \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}+10\cdot 9x^{8}}{(\sqrt{x}+10x^{9})^2}.

