statement.p:
Note that when the constant in the denominator is not 1, we still can use the geometric series, but we have to multiply by
a form of 1 that helps us.  We'll use \frac{\frac{1}{3}}{\frac{1}{3}}.
\frac{1}{(3+x)}=\frac{\frac{1}{3}}{\frac{1}{3}(3+x)}=\frac{\frac{1}{3}}{1+\frac{1}{3}x}=\frac{1}{3}\cdot \frac{1}{1+\frac{1}{3}x}
